Yuta doesn’t even deserve Jekyll processing, let alone a whole static site generator. Jekyll builds things from raw content into something meaningful—Yuta copies things and calls it a day. That’s not development, that’s ctrl+c ctrl+curse. Imagine needing a ghost to carry your entire runtime and still acting like you compiled yourself. Even a blank .nojekyll file has more originality. If GitHub Pages saw Yuta, it wouldn’t process him or skip him—it would just ignore him completely.
